<item>
            <title>[SPR-13570] JSON API support</title>
                <link>https://jira.spring.io/browse/SPR-13570</link>
                <project id="10000" key="SPR">Spring Framework</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://jsonapi.org/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;JSON API&lt;/a&gt; is a specification for how a client should request that resources be fetched or modified, and how a server should respond to those requests. Clients built around JSON API are able to take advantage of its features around efficiently caching responses, sometimes eliminating network requests entirely.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.baeldung.com/json-api-java-spring-web-app&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Eugen Baeldung blog post&lt;/a&gt; give some interesting insights about how to build a prototype that integrates &lt;a href=&quot;http://katharsis.io/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Katharsis&lt;/a&gt;, an interesting Java implementation of JSON API that is also compliant with HATEOAS. Katharsis does not provide a native Spring integration yet.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;JSON API support may be achieved by adding such support in Spring HATEOAS (if it makes sense), or providing Katharsis Spring integration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Ultimately, the goal of this feature is to provide support for the &lt;a href=&quot;http://jsonapi.org/implementations/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;client-side Javascript JSON API libraries&lt;/a&gt;, like the most advanced one &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/emberjs/data&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Ember Data&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Any feedback appreciated.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
